FAQs about origami

Where do I begin with origami and how can I find easy models?

Try browsing the board for guides, or other online resources listed below, for models you like and practice folding them.

A great way to begin at origami is to participate in the Let’s Fold Together threads >>>/po/lft - open up the PDF file and find a model you like, work on it, and discuss or post results.

http://en.origami-club.com
https://origami.me/diagrams/
https://www.origami-resource-center.com/free-origami-instructions.html
http://www.paperfolding.com/diagrams/

What paper should I use?

It depends on the model; for smaller models which involved 25 steps or fewer, 15 by 15 cm origami paper from a local craft store will be suitable. For larger models you will need larger or thinner paper, possibly from online shops. Boxpleated models require thin paper, such as sketching paper. Wet folded models require thicker paper, such as elephant hide.

https://www.origami-shop.com/en/

Hints and tips?

For folding, The best advice is to always fold as cleanly as possible, and take your time. Everything else comes with experience.

https://origami.me/beginners-guide/
https://origamiusa.org/glossary

What are ‘CPs’?

Crease patterns are a structural representations of origami models, shown as a schematic of lines; they are essentially origami models unfolded and laid flat. Lines on a crease pattern may be indicated by ‘mountain’ or ‘valley’ folds to show how the folds alternate. If you’re particularly skilled at origami, they become useful instructions for building models. A common base fold is usually discernable, all the intermediate details can be worked on from there.

https://blog.giladnaor.com/2008/08/folding-from-crease-patterns.html
http://www.origamiaustria.at/articles.php?lang=2#a4

>You don't think it would require balsa wood reinforcement or anything?
Depends on the size of the part but figure typical card stock is 90 lb so 300lb is over 3× as strong, plus the gelatine sizing that goes all the way through it makes it even stiffer when dry. If you use more of the same paper to laminate stiffeners into it or for things like door and window surrounds in a model like the OPs pic it's pretty much as stiff as balsa if not stiffer, especially if you rotate the grain 90°.

>Also you said it was like leather what tools do you use to do you detail work with it?
I use the outer edge of a small pair of surgical scissors drawn across it to make score and fold lines, a bookbinders folder/creaser to flatten folds uniformly, ball tip clay sculpting tools to burnish smooth areas in the rough textured stuff, Xacto knives to carve grooves and makes bevels, and leather tools to emboss some details and punch holes...I also made some grooved hardwood and metal blocks that I could stretch wet pieces into using a bamboo skewer to make half cylinder profiles to mimic things like auto trim and moldings and spars on boats. Most of the stuff I did with it was more architectural and vehicle modeling and art as opposed to decorative motifs.
Another cool thing you can do with it is to draw out curved folding lines and then run over them with a sewing machine with no thread set to a straight stitch...it creates just enough relief that folds will follow the perforations but the cotton fibers are long enough that it won't tear like non-rag paper.
Another way to look at it is that compositional it's like very thin and highly compacted felt, just stiffened with gelatin so it's almost like its plasticized.
